[[Category:Maldivian politicians]]
[[Category:Maldivian businesspeople]]

{{BLPunsourced|date=February 2009}}
[[Image:Zahir_hussain.jpg|thumb|Dr. M.Z. Hussain]]
'''Dr. Mohamed Zahir Hussain''' (Uncle) ([[Dhivehi]]:ޑރ. މުޙައްމަދު ޒާހިރު ޙުސައިން) was the former Minister of Youth and Sports of the [[Maldives]]. He is also the Chairman/Owner of the leading newspaper [[Haveeru Daily], which was established in 1978. Haveeru daily remains the most popular newspaper with the highest daily circulation to date. 

{{Maldives-politician-stub}}

[[Category:Maldivian politicians]]
[[Category:Maldivian businesspeople]]

{{BLPunsourced|date=February 2009}}
[[Image:Zahir_hussain.jpg|thumb|Dr. M.Z. Hussain]]
Dr. Mohamed Zahir Hussain,([[Dhivehi]]:ޑރ. މުޙައްމަދު ޒާހިރު ޙުސައިން) was the former Minister of Youth and Sports of the [[Maldives]]. He resigned from the post in the year 2005, since then he has been living a silent life, out of politics. He is also the Chairman/Owner of the leading newspaper [[Haveeru Daily], which was established in 1978. Haveeru Daily remains the most popular newspaper in the Maldives to date. 

{{Maldives-politician-stub}}

[[Category:Maldivian politicians]]
[[Category:Maldivian businesspeople]]

{{BLPunsourced|date=February 2009}}
[[Image:Zahir_hussain.jpg|thumb|Dr. M.Z. Hussain]]
Dr. Mohamed Zahir Hussain,([[Dhivehi]]:ޑރ. މުޙައްމަދު ޒާހިރު ޙުސައިން) was the former Minister of Youth and Sports of the [[Maldives]]. He resigned from the post in the year 2005, since then he has been living a silent life, out of politics. He is also the Chairman/Owner of the leading newspaper [[Haveeru Daily]] which was established in 1978. Haveeru Daily remains the most popular newspaper in the Maldives to date. 

{{Maldives-politician-stub}}

[[Category:Maldivian politicians]]
[[Category:Maldivian businesspeople]]

{{BLPunsourced|date=February 2009}}
[[Image:Zahir_hussain.jpg|thumb|Dr. M.Z. Hussain]]
Dr. Mohamed Zahir Hussain,([[Dhivehi]]:ޑރ. މުޙައްމަދު ޒާހިރު ޙުސައިން) was the former Minister of Youth and Sports of the [[Maldives]]. He resigned from the post in the year 2004 but was again appointed a senior minister (more a special envoy to the president) in 2006 and served until 2008 presidential election. Since then, Dr. Zahir has not been seen in politics. He is also the Chairman/Owner of the leading newspaper [[Haveeru Daily]] which was established in 1978. Haveeru Daily remains the most popular newspaper in the Maldives to date. 

{{Maldives-politician-stub}}

