[[Image:Zahir hussain.jpg|thumb|Dr. M.Z. Hussain]] Dr. '''Mohamed Zahir Hussain''',([[Dhivehi language|Dhivehi]]:ޑރ. މުޙައްމަދު ޒާހިރު ޙުސައިން) is the former Education Minister<ref>{{cite news |title=A Minister Who Goes To School Thrice A Week |work=[[New Straits Times]] |date=2 June 1989 |page=2 }}</ref> and Minister of Youth and Sports<ref>{{cite news |title=Lankan sportsmen invited to Maldives |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2002/09/20/new26.html |work=Daily News (Sri Lanka) |date=20 September 2002 |accessdate=16 March 2011 }}</ref> of the [[Maldives]]. He resigned from the post in the year 2004 but was again appointed a senior minister, a special advisor to the president,<ref>{{cite news |title=The President appoints three Senior Ministers and four Ministers |url=http://www.maldivesinfo.gov.mv/home/files/bulletinx_det.php?id_news=983 |work=Maldives News Bulletin |publisher=Department of Information |date=20 April 2008 |accessdate=16 March 2011 }}</ref> in 2006 and served until 2008 presidential election. He is also the Chairman/Owner of the newspaper [[Haveeru Daily]] which was established in 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.haveeru.com.mv/haveeru/ |title=About Haveeru Daily |publisher=[[Haveeru Daily]] |accessdate=16 March 2011 }}</ref>
