{{Short description|Chancellor of Maldives National University}}
[[File:147293 3f694919-a .jpg|thumb|Hussain in 2019]]
Dr. '''Mohamed Zahir Hussain''',([[Dhivehi language|Dhivehi]]:ޑރ. މުޙައްމަދު ޒާހިރު ޙުސައިން) was the [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of [[Maldives National University]]<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |date=20 March 2012 |title=Dr Zahir Hussain appointed as Chancellor |url=https://en.sun.mv/1987 |access-date=16 October 2023 |website=Sun}}</ref> and the former Minister of Education<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{cite news |title=A Minister Who Goes To School Thrice A Week |work=[[New Straits Times]] |date=2 June 1989 |page=2 }}</ref> as well as the Minister of Youth and Sports<ref>{{cite news |title=Lankan sportsmen invited to Maldives |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2002/09/20/new26.html |work=Daily News (Sri Lanka) |date=20 September 2002 |accessdate=16 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031021194814/http://www.dailynews.lk/2002/09/20/new26.html |archive-date=21 October 2003 |url-status=dead }}</ref> of the [[Maldives]]. He resigned from the post of Youth Minister in the year 2004 but was again appointed as a senior minister (a special advisor to the president)<ref>{{cite news |date=20 April 2008 |title=The President appoints three Senior Ministers and four Ministers |work=Maldives News Bulletin |publisher=Department of Information |url=http://www.maldivesinfo.gov.mv/home/files/bulletinx_det.php?id_news=983 |accessdate=16 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231016072721/http://www.maldivesinfo.gov.mv/home/files/bulletinx_det.php?id_news=983 |archive-date=16 October 2023}}</ref> in 2006 and served in the cabinet of [[President of the Maldives|President]] [[Maumoon Abdul Gayoom]] until 2008 presidential election. In 2008, he was conferred the distinguished "Order of Izzuddin" by [[President of the Maldives|President]] [[Maumoon Abdul Gayoom]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Maldives News Bulletin, 17-11-2008 |url=http://www.maldivesinfo.gov.mv/home/files/bulletinx_det.php?id_news=1070 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231016072423/http://www.maldivesinfo.gov.mv/home/files/bulletinx_det.php?id_news=1070 |archive-date=16 October 2023 |access-date=16 October 2023 |website=Department of Information}}</ref> He is also the Chairman/Owner of the newspaper [[Haveeru Daily]] which was established in 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.haveeru.com.mv/haveeru/ |title=About Haveeru Daily |publisher=[[Haveeru Daily]] |accessdate=16 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722223048/http://www.haveeru.com.mv/haveeru/ |archive-date=22 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> His wife was Naalia Ibrahim Kaleyfaan''',''' who passed away in 2021 while receiving treatment at [[ADK Hospital]]. She was a teacher at [[Aminiyya School|Aminiya School]] for 25 years, and the first chancellor of the Islamic University of Maldives.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news |last=Zalif |first=Zunana |date=17 April 2021 |title=Spouse of Dr. Zahir Hussain, Naaila Ibrahim Kaleyfaan passes away |work=raajje.mv |url=https://raajje.mv/index.php/98462 |url-status=live |access-date=16 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231016071940/https://raajje.mv/index.php/98462 |archive-date=16 October 2023}}</ref> Zahir has three children – Leena Zahir Hussain, Vail Zahir Hussain and Lubna Zahir Hussain.<ref name=":1" />

